steps.text:
You’re seeing the intended behavior in that early Tailwind version: `border-dotted`/`border-dashed` are style modifiers, not complete borders. The reset prevents them from creating the browser’s default `medium`-width border by themselves.

Use a width utility as well:

```css
.example {
  @apply border border-dotted;
}
```

That expands effectively to:

```css
.example {
  border-width: 0;
  border: 1px solid currentColor; /* Tailwind’s configured default */
  border-style: dotted;
}
```

The ordering matters: `@apply border border-dotted`, not `@apply border-dotted border`, since the `border` shorthand would reset the style back to `solid`.

If `.border-dotted` appears to work in markup, it is likely being combined with `border` (or another `border-*` width utility). On its own, the reset correctly leaves it with no visible border.
